      passage: `On the Precision of Words

George Orwell's 1946 essay "Politics and the English Language" contains an observation that has lost none of its force: bad writing is not merely an aesthetic problem but a moral and political one. It is the instrument through which uncomfortable truths are obscured, through which atrocities are committed in the passive voice, through which the perpetrators of institutional failure vanish behind impersonal constructions.

The precision Orwell advocated is not the same as technical vocabulary, nor is it the avoidance of complexity. It is the matching of language to thought — the use of specific words where general ones would conceal, concrete images where abstractions would fog, active constructions where passive ones would erase agency. "The villagers were resettled" is not merely less precise than "soldiers forced the villagers from their homes at gunpoint"; it is morally different, because it removes from the sentence the humans who made a choice to do something to other humans.

This matters because language shapes perception as much as it reflects it. The vocabulary available to a person determines, in part, the distinctions they can make and the thoughts they can think. A person who has only one word for anger and cannot distinguish between resentment, indignation, contempt, exasperation, and fury is not merely less articulate than someone who has all five — they are less capable of understanding their own emotional life and, consequently, of managing it.

The acquisition of a precise, extensive vocabulary is therefore not an aesthetic luxury but a cognitive tool — one that expands the range of perceptions, distinctions, and arguments available to the person who possesses it.`,
